  <h1>Champion Commercial Dishwasher Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>Champion Industries out of Winston-Salem, North Carolina has been building commercial dishwashers for over 130 years. That's not a marketing line — it's an operational reality. They call themselves "The Dishwashing Machine Specialist," and they mean it: no ovens, no refrigeration, just warewashing. The brand is part of Ali Group, the Italian equipment holding company that also owns Moyer Diebel (the Canadian counterpart). In the LA market, Champion shows up most in the places where volume is the primary concern — LAUSD school kitchens, university dining halls at UCLA and USC, hotel banquet dishrooms, and stadium concession prep operations. These are accounts where a machine running 500 racks a day needs to keep running.</p>

  <p>What we run into most on Champion service calls in SoCal isn't usually a catastrophic failure. It's the PRV. Champion's pressure reducing valve is a component that doesn't get mentioned in generic dishwasher repair content because it's not a standard failure point on other brands — but on Champion door-type and conveyor machines, the PRV drifts over time and causes wash pressure that's too high (damaging dishes) or too low (dishes not cleaning). We carry PRV assemblies on our commercial trucks specifically for this. The second most common Champion call is the ventless heat recovery system on the DH6000 — operators love that it doesn't need a ventilation hood, but most don't know the heat exchanger inside it needs periodic descaling. In LA hard water, it needs it quarterly.</p>

  <p>$120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair. Same-day response throughout SoCal. Call <strong>{phone}</strong>.</p>

  <h2>Champion Equipment We Service</h2>

  <h3>UH Series — Undercounter Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>The UH-330B, UH-130B, and UH-130ADA are Champion's undercounter machines — compact, high-temp sanitizing units for bar service, server stations, and smaller food service operations throughout LA. The UH series uses a high-temperature final rinse without a chemical sanitizer — booster heater required. In LA's hard water environment, the booster element scales at a predictable rate. But the failure mode we see more often than the booster on Champion undercounters is the door safety switch. The UH series has a door safety interlock that prevents the cycle from starting if the door isn't fully sealed. In a high-cycle bar or server station where the machine runs 200+ door cycles per shift, the switch contact wears. The machine won't start, the operator assumes it's broken. Half the time it's the door switch, not anything more serious.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> UH-330B, UH-130B, UH-130ADA</p>

  <h3>DH Series — Door-Type Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>The DH2000 and DH6000 are Champion's door-type machines — the workhorses of mid-to-high volume restaurant and institutional kitchens. The DH6000 is the more interesting machine technically: it includes Champion's ventless heat recovery system, which condenses exhaust steam internally instead of requiring a ventilation hood. This makes the DH6000 attractive for kitchens where a hood over the dishwasher isn't practical — which describes a significant number of LA's older restaurant buildings and retrofitted kitchen spaces.</p>
  <p>The ventless heat recovery system on the DH6000 has a heat exchanger that Champion doesn't always emphasize in their operator documentation. The exchanger condenses steam using incoming cold water — in LA hard water, the exchanger passages develop scale deposits over time, reducing the condensation efficiency. When this happens, steam starts escaping into the kitchen the same way it does on a non-ventless machine — operators notice the kitchen getting humid, but don't connect it to dishwasher maintenance. We descale the DH6000's heat recovery exchanger as part of every service call on that model in the LA market.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> DH2000, DH6000, DH6000 (ventless heat recovery), DL2000, DH-2000, DH-5000</p>

  <h3>PP / PRO Series — Passthrough &amp; Door-Type</h3>
  <p>Champion's PRO series (64 PRO through 140 PRO) and PP series are the mid-range door-type and passthrough machines found throughout LA's food service density — neighborhood restaurants in the SGV, hotel dining rooms in the South Bay, and volume food service operations from Koreatown to the Westside. These machines run single-tank or dual-tank configurations. The 90-second cycle timer is a common failure point on older PRO series machines — when the timer fails, cycles run too long or don't complete properly. It's a straightforward parts swap, but operators often assume it's a more significant mechanical failure because the behavior is erratic. We keep timer assemblies for the common PRO series models stocked.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> PP-10 through PP-100, 64 PRO through 140 PRO</p>

  <h3>E-Series — Conveyor Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Champion's E-Series single-tank and two-tank conveyor machines serve the highest-volume operations in SoCal — the LAUSD central production kitchens, the UCLA and USC dining operations, hotel banquet dishrooms along the Wilshire corridor, and event venue operations. The E-Series single-tank 44 and the two-tank 64 model handle the volume where a door-type machine simply can't keep up. Conveyor Champion service has specific failure modes: the table limit switch that stops the conveyor when dishes are backed up at the output end is a high-wear component in heavy-use operations (it's tripped repeatedly by operators who are loading faster than the machine can process). The conveyor drive chain itself requires periodic tension adjustment — a loose chain causes erratic conveyor speed and incomplete wash coverage.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> E-Series Single-Tank 44, Single-Tank w/ Prewash 66 PW, Two-Tank w/ Prewash 64, B-Tronic series</p>

  <h2>The PRV — What It Is and Why It Matters on Champion Equipment</h2>

  <p>The pressure reducing valve is a component that almost never gets discussed in generic commercial dishwasher content. On Champion door-type and conveyor machines, the PRV regulates the incoming water pressure to the wash system — Champion's spray arm design is engineered for a specific operating pressure range, typically 20 PSI. LA's municipal water pressure varies significantly by zone and can run considerably higher than this in many areas. Without a functioning PRV maintaining the correct wash pressure, the machine either under-washes (PRV stuck low — dishes come out with residue) or damages lighter dishware (PRV stuck high — too much spray force).</p>

  <p>We check PRV function on every Champion door-type and conveyor call as a standard step, regardless of what the presenting complaint is. The PRV is inexpensive to replace and has an outsized effect on wash quality. On older Champion machines that have been in service for 5+ years in high-volume kitchens, PRV drift is one of the first things we look at when wash quality has degraded gradually — before assuming it's a pump, heating element, or chemical dosing issue.</p>

  <h2>Recent Champion Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"DH6000 ventless — steam in the kitchen, hotel banquet kitchen Downtown LA"</h3>
  <p>Hotel banquet kitchen, DH6000 with the ventless heat recovery option — installed specifically because the dishroom didn't have adequate exhaust ventilation for a standard machine. About 18 months into service, the kitchen started getting noticeably more humid during dishwashing runs. No error codes, machine cycling normally, but the steam management was clearly degrading. We found scale buildup in the heat recovery exchanger passages reducing condensation efficiency by roughly 40%. Full exchanger descale with Champion-approved deliming agent, verified exhaust air quality post-service. Humidity back to normal. Set the hotel on quarterly exchanger descaling — they'd assumed the ventless system required no maintenance because it had no traditional exhaust components. It does. Just different ones.</p>

  <h3>"E-Series conveyor jam, LAUSD kitchen, table limit switch failure"</h3>
  <p>School kitchen E-Series conveyor stopping mid-run repeatedly — the table limit switch at the output end was tripping falsely. The switch had worn from high-cycle use (a school kitchen running lunch service for 600+ students generates significant conveyor throughput). The switch contact had developed intermittent failure — it would trip randomly even when the output table was clear. Replaced the table limit switch assembly, adjusted the conveyor chain tension while there (it had loosened from extended service), tested through a full lunch service run. No stoppages. Left the facilities manager with a conveyor chain tension check protocol — it's a monthly adjustment in high-volume applications.</p>

  <h3>"UH-130B undercounter — won't start, bar Mid-City"</h3>
  <p>Called by a bar operator — UH-130B simply wouldn't initiate a cycle. Power was on, water supply was fine. Door safety switch had failed — the switch contact was no longer registering door closure even when the door was fully sealed. The machine's interlock was preventing cycle start as designed. Replaced the door safety switch with an OEM Champion part, tested through 10 cycles. Bar was back in service within 45 minutes of arrival. The operator had assumed the machine needed major repair because of the total failure to start. It was a $45 part and 20 minutes of labor once diagnosed.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>My Champion dishwasher won't start at all — what's the most likely cause?</strong><br>
  On Champion UH undercounters and DH door-type machines, a complete failure to start is most often the door safety switch rather than a more serious mechanical failure. The door interlock prevents cycle initiation if the door isn't registering as fully closed — when the switch contact wears or fails, it can stop the machine even with the door correctly sealed. We diagnose this on-site before assuming anything more complex is involved. Call {phone} — we can often resolve a no-start Champion call in a single visit.</p>

  <p><strong>What is the PRV and how do I know if it's causing my wash quality problems?</strong><br>
  The pressure reducing valve regulates incoming water pressure to Champion's wash system. When it drifts, dishes either come out with residue (low pressure) or lighter items get damaged from excessive spray force (high pressure). Gradual wash quality degradation that doesn't have an obvious cause — no error codes, temperatures correct, chemicals dosing correctly — is often a PRV drift issue on Champion equipment. We check it on every door-type and conveyor call.</p>

  <p><strong>Does the Champion DH6000 ventless system require maintenance?</strong><br>
  Yes. The ventless heat recovery system has an internal heat exchanger that condenses exhaust steam using incoming cold water. In LA's hard water, this exchanger develops scale deposits that reduce condensation efficiency over time — you'll notice the kitchen getting more humid during dishwashing runs. Quarterly descaling of the heat recovery exchanger is appropriate for SoCal. We descale it as part of every DH6000 service call in this market.</p>

  <p><strong>How often should Champion equipment be descaled in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Quarterly for booster heaters and heat exchangers. Monthly spray arm and filter inspection. LA municipal water at 250–350 ppm TDS is harder than the national average — the manufacturer's standard annual descaling schedule isn't appropriate for this market.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you carry OEM Champion parts?</strong><br>
  Yes — door safety switches, PRV assemblies, 90-second cycle timers, table limit switches, booster elements, pump seals, and spray arm assemblies for UH, DH, PP, and E-Series machines. Most common parts are available same-day from our commercial parts network.</p>

